		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1514135"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>
					Originally Posted by <strong>Ludarian</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=40c2bdabec29a0d99e6efb213de34f64&amp;p=1514117#post1514117" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost.gif" border="0" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">I have a dedicated windows server with 1and1.com.  Even the first day my server was set up I started getting brute force SQL Server sa login attempts from all over the globe.  SQL Server logs failures in the Event log.<br />
<br />
It's still happening.  I've changed the sa username just to stay safe.  I'm sure it's also getting brute force attacks for Administrator login too but those aren't being logged anywhere.  Feel pretty helpless that there's not anything I can do out of the box to stop it.  I'm sure there are some windows utilities that would help but who knows how expensive/intrusive they are.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>Hm I've never used windows server or sql server even. I have mysql's port closed (at the router) and use putty to tunnel if necessary.<br />
<br />
Depending on how much control you have over the server, you could change SQL server's port to the non default one (I assume). That might cut down on the attacks a little bit. I'm sure if I had sshd listen on a different port I'd lose some of the break in attempts. MySQL also allows you to limit users to IP addresses, though this might not be an option for sql server.</div>
		<!-- / message -->

		

		

		

		

		

	</td>
